{{Infobox cricketer | name = | image = | country = Ireland | fullname = Patrick Henry Pearse Waldron | birth_date = 5 February 1917 | birth_place = [[Limerick]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Ireland]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2008|12|26|1917|2|5}} | death_place = [[Dublin]], [[Leinster]], Ireland | nickname = | family = | batting = Right-handed | bowling = | role = | club1 = [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] | year1 = 1946&ndash;1947 | columns = 1 | column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]] | matches1 = 4 | runs1 = 99 | bat avg1 = 12.37 | 100s/50s1 = –/– | top score1 = 32 | deliveries1 = 0 | wickets1 = – | bowl avg1 = – | fivefor1 = – | tenfor1 = – | best bowling1 = – | catches/stumpings1 = –/– | date = 7 November | year = 2018 | source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/player/24530.html Cricinfo }}
'''Patrick Henry Pearse Waldron''' (5 February 1917 &ndash; 26 December 2008) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] first-class [[cricket]]er.
Waldron was born at [[Limerick]] in February 1917, and was educated at [[Catholic University School|Catholic University School, Dublin]].<ref name="CE">{{cite web|url=https://www.cricketeurope.com/IRELAND/PLAYERS/426/index.shtml |title=Player profile: Patrick Henry Pearse Waldron |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref> Obtaining a special dispensation from the [[Archbishop of Dublin (Roman Catholic)|Archbishop of Dublin]], he went up to [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]] to study law.<ref name="CE"/> Playing his club cricket in Dublin for [[Merrion Cricket Club|Merrion]], Waldron made his debut in [[first-class cricket]] for [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] against [[Scotland cricket team|Scotland]] at [[Glenpark Cricket Ground|Greenock]] in 1946.<ref name="FCM">{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26910/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Paddy Waldron |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref> He made three further first-class appearances for Scotland, all in 1947. One of these came against Scotland at [[Richard Beamish Cricket Grounds|Cork]], while the other two came against [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] and [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] on Ireland's tour of England.<ref name="FCM"/> Across his four first-class matches, Waldron scored 99 runs at an [[batting average|average]] of 12.37, with a highest score of 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26910/f_Batting_by_Team.html |title=First-class Batting and Fielding For Each Team by Paddy Waldron |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref> After completing his legal studies, he was called to the bar at the [[King's Inns]] in 1948.<ref name="CE"/> He contiuned to play club cricket for Merrion until 1953, having debuted for the club in 1936.<ref name="CE"/> At the time of his death in 2008, he was the oldest surviving Irish first-class cricketer,<ref name="CE"/> having succeeded [[Noel Mahony]] following his death in 2006.
